{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f06bbc94-e2dd-4a84-8468-72bb6480c300","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Place this file at **`.vscode/mcp.json`** in your workspace root.\n- The server communicates over **stdin/stdout** (`\"type\": \"stdio\"`), which is the standard for local MCP servers.\n- `dotnet run` builds and launches the project automatically.\n- If you've already published the app, you can point `command` directly at the compiled binary instead.\n\nAfter saving, open the **Copilot Chat** panel in agent mode — VS Code will automatically discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2413dc9e-e3a0-468a-9086-0183b4fae332","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet in this directory, but the user says they built it. They're just asking for configuration guidance. Let me provide the answer directly.","outputTokens":279,"requestId":"5C4F:1C6615:1CD32D3:1FF068D:69FA933A"},"id":"92adad50-00a4-429f-a455-4d678a2a5000","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:02:58.031Z","parentId":"8ffebd6b-ef3b-4e4e-9614-c36dc2570b8d"}
